fix: bailout module.exports for eliminate interop default property access (#3369)

<!-- Thank you for contributing! -->

### Description
1. The interop for `module.exports` case is complex, it is hard to makes
sure it is safe to optimize, so only optimize the interop `default`
property access, if all exports from the target cjs module is static
`exports.prop`, or it `module.exports = require('./mod'),
for the second condition, it is used to make sure the react pattern is
optimized.
2. When cjs module use `module.exports` to export a function, e.g.
```js
// index.js
iimport mod from './cjs.js'

console.log(mod.call({}, 1, 2))

// cjs.js

module.exports = function (a, b) {
  return a  + b
}
```

after bundle, 

```js
// cjs.js
var require_cjs = __commonJS({
  "cjs.js"(exports, module) {
    module.exports = function(a, b) {
      return a + b;
    };
  }
});

// entry.js
var import_cjs = __toESM(require_cjs());
console.log(import_cjs.default.call({}, 1, 2));
```
the `import_cjs` now is 
```bash
Function { default: [Function (anonymous)] }
```
So `import_cjs.xxx` no more eq to `import_cjs.default.xxx`

If `module.exports` is assigned with a object literal, for most cases it
should worked except when one property is
`__esModule`, due to the cjs is so dynamic, bailout for `module.exports`
assignmentExpr for now, for `React` case it should still worked.
3. Closed #3364
